# State machine and multi-writer discipline

## Rule

When changing state, status, progress, counters, permissions, ownership, or any
user-visible fact, identify the single authoritative writer and the single
canonical reader.

## Checklist

1. Search for every writer of the field, event, status, or query key.
2. Search for every reader that renders, branches, bills, authorizes, or queues
   based on the fact.
3. Define the allowed states and transitions. Impossible states should be
   impossible in code, not merely unlikely.
4. If two async paths can write the same fact, choose one writer or add a version,
   timestamp, lock, transaction, compare-and-swap, idempotency key, or state
   transition guard.
5. If UI and backend both derive the same fact, document which side is source of
   truth and how the other side hydrates.
6. For optimistic UI, define rollback behavior and prevent late server events from
   overwriting newer user intent.

## Pre-commit check

- [ ] Every writer was grepped.
- [ ] Every reader was grepped.
- [ ] State transitions are explicit.
- [ ] Late async responses cannot overwrite newer state.
- [ ] Tests cover the race or impossible-state boundary.
